Logistic Regression

1. Read the Titanic dataset on blackboard into a data frame

titanic <- read.csv("C:/Users/starw/OneDrive/Documents/NJCU Spring Semester/FINC614_Intro to Data science/Data Sets/Titanic.csv", sep=",")

Removing NA from our data.

titanic_cleaned <- na.omit(titanic)

create a new data frame with distinct rows

titanic_distinct <- distinct(titanic_cleaned)
titanic_distinct$Survived <- factor(titanic_distinct$Survived)

b. Split the dataset into a training and test data set

set.seed(12345)
intrain <- createDataPartition(titanic_distinct$Survived,p=0.70,list = FALSE)
train <- titanic_distinct[intrain,]
test <- titanic_distinct[-intrain,]

c. Fit a logistic regression model for predicting whether a passenger survived

#Fit model
modFit <- train(Survived ~Sex + Age + Pclass, method='glm', data=train, family=binomial(link='logit'))
